Their social history is a case study in (apparent) success of a migrant group resettling in a totally alien environment, "assimilating," yet preserving a unique ethnic identity. Contents: Roll 113.                   </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>Record group 61-2 consists in part of federal census records of the 1880 census for Michigan for products of manufacturers. The schedule offers name of corporation, company or individual producing articles to the annual value of $550; name of business, manufacture or product; capital invested in real and personal estate in the business; quantity, kind and value or raw material used; kind of motive power; average number of hands employed; wages; quantity, kind and value of annual production. Occasionally includes narrative reports on fisheries and other industry not mentioned on form. Includes special schedules on agricultural implements; paper mills; boots and shoes, leather (tanned and curried); lumber and saw mills, brick and tile works; flour and grist mills, cheese, butter and condensed milk factories; and slaughtering and meat packing, salt works. </abstract>
